<HEAD>Former Charleston Mayor Earns Early Release For Good Behavior</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Roark </PERSON> will be released from federal prison 18 days early because he has been a model prisoner while serving time for cocaine possession, authorities said Friday. <PERSON> Roark </PERSON>, who was sentenced to 179 days in prison in November after pleading guilty to cocaine possession, will be released July 20, said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Sizer </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Correctional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Petersburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va </LOCATION>. The former <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> mayor and <LOCATION> Kanawha </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> prosecutor will be credited with 16 days of time for good behavior and two days for time served after his arrest, <PERSON> Sizer </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Roark </PERSON>, who earned the nickname `` Mad Dog'' for his zealous prosecution of drug offenders during his days as <LOCATION> Kanawha </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> prosecutor, had just started his second four-year term when he was indicted. <PERSON> Roark </PERSON> was indicted in July 1987 on 27 cocaine-related counts and three charges of conspiracy to obstruct justice. All but six misdemeanor possession counts were dropped in a plea bargain in which he agreed to resign his office. A spokesman for the State Bar this week said <PERSON> Roark </PERSON> will be called in for a hearing soon after his release. The bar is deciding whether to revoke or suspend his license as a result of his guilty plea. <PERSON> Roark </PERSON> served as an assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney in western <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> in the mid-1970s before returning to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s largest city to begin his political career in 1978 He never lost an election and had been talked up as a future <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> candidate for governor or <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> before his legal problems started.
