<FIRST>r a PM-PitBullCollars     07-02 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pit Bull Collars,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pit Bulls, Other Animals Must Wear Fluorescent Collars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALVESTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Postal workers cheered as the city council approved a law requiring vicious animals to wear fluorescent yellow collars and some owners to take out liability insurance on their pets. The law, passed Thursday in response to pit bull attacks, requires vicious animals to wear the collars, which signify the wearer has attacked humans or other animals or has been legally declared likely to do so without provocation. The ordinance also requires that an animal declared vicious be tattooed with the number that appears on the permit allowing the owner to keep it inside the city limits. In addition, owners of vicious animals can be forced to carry at least $ 100,000 in liability insurance to keep the pets in the city and can be fined up to $ 2,000 for violations of the new ordinance. Local letter carriers who gathered in council chambers cheered Thursday when the ordinance was passed. A <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION> postal worker was severely bitten by a pit bull in January, and an 83-year-old man died from wounds inflicted in a November attack by two pit bulls. `` I hope this action today will save lives in the future,'' Mayor <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Coggeshall </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
