<HEAD>Boston Symphony Orchestra Celebrates 50th Anniversary of First
Shed Concert</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LENOX, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Tanglewood </LOCATION>, the summer home of the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Symphony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orchestra </ORGANIZATION>, observed the 50th birthday of its Music Shed with a 50-candle cake and a reunion of musicians and ushers from the shed's first concert. Also in honor of the half-century-old concert hall, symphony trustees voted Friday to rename the Music Shed after the late conductor <PERSON> Serge </PERSON> <PERSON> Koussevitzky </PERSON>, founder of the prestigious summer music festival who inaugurated the hall with a performance of <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON>'s Ninth Symphony and <PERSON> Bach </PERSON>'s Cantata No. 80 in 1938. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kidder </PERSON>, symphony president, played tapes of <PERSON> Koussevitzky </PERSON>, giving his reasons for choosing <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON>'s Ninth Symphony for the inaugural performance, which the symphony orchestra played again Friday night. `` On this significant day in the musical life, I have selected to give the Ninth Symphony not only because it is the greatest masterpiece in the musical literature, but also to hear the voices of <LOCATION> Tanglewood </LOCATION> repeating -LRB- German poet <PERSON> Johann </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Shiller </PERSON>'s great words calling all nations to brotherhood,'' <PERSON> Koussevitsky </PERSON> said on one of the tapes. During a break in the program, <PERSON> Kidder </PERSON> also introduced several people who had been at the 1938 performance, including three ushers. Orchestra members and concert-goers who were present at the Aug. 4, 1938, inaugural performance were honored at a luncheon Friday at <PERSON> Koussevitzky </PERSON>'s home, <PERSON> Seranak </PERSON>.
