<HEAD>Ligachev Reveals Secrets Behind Rise Of Gorbachev</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Yegor </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON>, the No. 2 man in the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>, provided an unprecedented look into the inner workings of the Soviet leadership with his description of the events that brought <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to power. <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> said Friday at the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> conference that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> had crucial support from himself, <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gromyko </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chebrikov </PERSON> when he became party general secretary in March 1985. <PERSON> Gromyko </PERSON>, now president, was foreign minister at the time. <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON>, recounting emotions and experiences in a manner rare for a member of the traditionally stoic party Politburo, disputed claims from ousted <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Communist Party boss <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> that he had slowed reform. He said he had been deeply worried about the fate of the country during the final days of <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>, who ruled from 1964 to 1982 in a `` time of stagnation.'' More `` very disquieting days and hours'' came when the party elite assembled to choose a successor to <PERSON> Konstantin </PERSON> <PERSON> U. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chernenko </PERSON> in March 1985, <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> said. `` Fate put me in the center'' of action, he said. `` We could have made quite different decisions. And, sometimes I think: What would have happened to the country after that?'' he told the conference delegates. With the support of <PERSON> Chebrikov </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gromyko </PERSON>, Politburo member <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomentsev </PERSON> and some regional party leaders, `` the only correct decision was taken,'' he added. <PERSON> Gromyko </PERSON> made the nominating speech proposing <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> as general secretary after <PERSON> Chernenko </PERSON>'s death, but <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON>'s account was the first to suggest Solomentsev had supported <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. His comments appeared to confirm rumors that circulated at the time that former <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> party boss <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Grishin </PERSON>, an ally of <PERSON> Chernenko </PERSON> and <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>, had made a last-minute attempt to secure the leadership. <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON>'s statements, which were televised, also could boost <PERSON> Gromyko </PERSON> and <PERSON> Solomentsev </PERSON> a day after they were criticized by name at the four-day conference, which ended Friday. <PERSON> Gromyko </PERSON>, 78, was foreign minister for 28 years before accepting the largely ceremonial presidency in July 1985. He and <PERSON> Solomentsev </PERSON> have sat on the policy-setting <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> since the early 1960s. `` The country came to a crisis'' before <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> became leader, <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> said. He spoke of corruption, lack of discipline and alcoholism. Because of a lack of frankness, even `` the party was in danger,'' he said. `` All revolutionary parties that died did so because they were afraid to talk about their weaknesses,'' he said. <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> spoke of his career during the <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON> years. `` In the years of stagnation I worked and lived in <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader in the Siberian city of <LOCATION> Tomsk </LOCATION> from 1965-83. `` I say with pride that I built socialism. And there were millions of such people.'' Referring with a touch of humor to the Russian practice of sending misfits and disidents to <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> said, `` Perhaps we worked like that because we knew that they would n't send us farther than <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>.''
