<HEAD>Commander Says Soviets Not Defeated in Afghanistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Party, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The commander of Soviet troops in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> said they served with honor and were not defeated, but two influential officials criticized the decision to intervene in the fight against U.S.-backed rebels. `` We came to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> not to win battles, but to defend women and children, villages and cities. And we have performed our duty with honor,'' Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Gromov </PERSON> told the national <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> conference on Friday. The <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> entered in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in December 1979, and more than 100,000 troops were helping the Marxist government fight the Moslem guerrillas until a withdrawal agreement was signed in April. <PERSON> Gromov </PERSON>, who told reporters this week that the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> is no longer taking active part in the fighting, rejected claims that the Soviet force was beaten. <PERSON> Grigory </PERSON> <PERSON> Baklanov </PERSON>, editor of the literary journal <LOCATION> Znamya </LOCATION>, said the decision to intervene was made `` in defiance of the machinery of democracy.'' He said some non-voting members of the ruling Politburo learned about the decision only by reading the newspapers. `` I receive many letters from mothers,'' he said in remarks broadcast by Soviet television. `` They ask, ` How did this happen? Who supported it?''' <PERSON> Yevgeny </PERSON> <PERSON> Primakov </PERSON> said the decision under late President <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON> was made `` without a proper examination of the possible alternatives of a political resolution.'' The remarks by <PERSON> Primakov </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION> and International Relations of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, were provided by the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency. The discussion of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> on the fourth and final day of the conference lacked the sharp character of debates on the bolder news media, the economy and other issues. But coupled with Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s own critique and some personal criticism during the conference of President <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gromyko </PERSON> _ the foreign minister for 28 years _ it indicated serious dissatisfaction with the conduct of foreign policy earlier this decade. Soviet military officials have refused to criticize the orders to fight in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, which cost them more than 13,000 dead and 35,000 wounded. According to the terms of an April 14 agreement signed in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, a fifth of the 100,000 Soviet soldiers have left <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and the remainder must be gone by Feb. 15, 1989. In his opening address to the party conference Tuesday, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> praised the soldiers who served in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, but the criticism of <PERSON> Baklanov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Primakov </PERSON> echoed other remarks of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. `` It sometimes happened that even decisions of vital importance were taken by a narrow circle of people without collective, comprehensive examination of analysis, on occasion without properly consulting friends either. This led to an inadequate reaction to international events and to the policies of other states, if not to mistaken decisions,'' he said. The <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> agreement and withdrawal from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> `` have become an international milestone in the political settlement of regional conflicts, which are fraught with a danger to the world as a whole and which hinder the progress of the nations,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said. He said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> too often in the past has emphasized military strength rather than political skill. He has been extremely critical of the rule of <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON> as a period of stagnation and corruption. In an address Thursday, a local party official called for a pair of officials long influential in foreign affairs to step down because they had been part of <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>'s administration. Prompted by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to name names, <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Melnikov </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Siberian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Komi </LOCATION> region called for <PERSON> Gromyko </PERSON> and <PERSON> Georgy </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbatov </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A.-Canada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> for the past 21 years, to step down. Other Soviet officials in recent months have suggested that the decision to send soldiers into <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> was a mistake, but their comments were in less - influential and less-public forums
