<HEAD>Soviet Bloc Allies Generally Praise Party Conference</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Party, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> conference in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> generally brought praise from <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, where the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>'s new policies are pressuring leaders to reform their own countries `` In <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, in our party, we are deeply satisfied with the course of the <ORGANIZATION> CPSU </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- conference,'' said a commentary of the official Polish news agency <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION>. `` With satisfaction we receive the changes brought by perestroika and new thinking.'' <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> have gone the farthest in matching or even exceeding Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms in the economy and politics. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, who closed the four-day conference Friday, will be paying a six-day visit to <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> beginning July 11. The `` new thinking'' at the conference `` creates fresh possibilities of a gradual demilitarization and humanization of international relations,'' Polish <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Stefan </PERSON> <PERSON> Staniszewski </PERSON> told a news conference Thursday. In <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, where officials privately say they are waiting to see whether <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> will strengthen his position at the conference, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> daily Rude Pravo said the event `` will be an inspiration and a source of practical enlightment for us.'' If the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader gets a mandate for more radical reforms, it would increase pressur