<HEAD>Soviet Television Gets into Glasnost Act with Live Interviews</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Party, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State-run television interrupted its usual bland fare for spicy, live interviews after a disgraced leader pleaded for forgiveness in a dramatic speech at a national <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> conference. One delegate told a television correspondent that the conference discussion about ousted <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> party chief <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> was a healthy sign that democracy and `` glasnost,'' leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of openness, was taking hold. `` We can speak our minds openly and directly, without being afraid of anything,'' said <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Maximov </PERSON>, a balding metalworker from the Siberian town of <LOCATION> Biisk </LOCATION>. During a Friday afternoon break in the final session of the first party conference in 47 years, Soviet television broadcast the live interviews in the lobby of the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>'s Palace of Congresses with some of the 5,000 delegates. Most of the discussion during the broadcast focused on what one delegate called the highlight of Friday's session of the four-day conference, the speech by <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>, a former <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> protege. `` It's the most heated discussion we have heard in a long time,'' a gray-haired delegate told the television correspondent. A studio anchorman began the 30-minute broadcast and then switched live to the correspondent on the scene. Delegates had just ended floor debate about <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>'s speech, in which he asked to be cleared of blame for criticizing other Soviet leaders and saying reform was proceeding too slowly. The discussion spilled over into the television interviews. Some delegates told viewers they supported <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>, while others condemned his remarks as `` politically incorrect.'' <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> was fired as <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> party boss and removed from his post as a non-voting member of the ruling Politburo after a bitter speech to the party's <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> last October, in which he complained that economic reforms had stalled and asked to be relieved of his duties. His speech at that meeting has never been published. <PERSON> Maximov </PERSON>, the delegate from <LOCATION> Biisk </LOCATION>, said it is difficult for people to make up their minds about whether <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>'s criticism was justified because his <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> speech remains secret. `` Glasnost must be deep; then such questions would n't arise,'' he told the television interviewer. During the conference, Soviet television and radio provided periodic newsbriefs with highlights of speeches and live interviews with delegates. The popular evening news program `` Vremya,'' which reportedly has a nightly audience of tens of millions of Soviets, departed from its usual fare of dull reports about the latest beet harvest or other economic achievement to carry extensive coverage on the party conference. The nightly program normally runs 45 minutes but Friday it continued for three hours with extensive clips of <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>'s address and remarks by his critics. Videotape showed <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> appealing for political rehabilitation, and when there was a roar from the delegates <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> waved his hands and asked that <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> be allowed to continue. `` Vremya'' directors apparently felt the <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> issue was so important that they continued showing the taped reports even after <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> began his speech closing the conference. Soviet radio carried <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s speech live and Vremya later broadcast a recording.
