<HEAD>Pornography Outlets Nationwide Charged In Obscene Mailings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents, grafs 13-14 bgng: Ward said ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 People who received unsolicited pornography sparked an investigation that authorities said resulted in federal charges against companies responsible for much of the country's sexually oriented mailings Indictments unsealed Friday in eight states charged 20 people and 14 companies under a section of federal law that makes it a crime to use the mails for advertising or distributing obscene material. `` Project Postporn,'' the official moniker for the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department-Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> probe, specifically targeted hard-core pornography, which depicts actual sexual acts. Mailings usually arrived at homes addressed to adults, children or simply `` resident,'' said <PERSON> Brent </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney for <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> and chairman of the attorney general's subcommittee on obscenity. `` They arrive unsolicited in innocuous-looking envelopes in the homes of unsuspecting people who have never subscribed to pornography, do not want it in their homes and are never going to order any obscene material,'' <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said at a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> news conference Friday. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Swagerty </PERSON>, assistant chief postal inspector, said such mailings had increased in recent years, prompting more than 350,000 people to file postal service forms requesting that they not receive sexually oriented material though the mail. About 100,000 of them were filed in the last year, he said. The investigation began a year ago in response to complaints, officials said. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said it had targeted only `` hard-core obscenity which the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has held is not protected by the First Amendment.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s test of obscenity is that the material, taken as a whole, has to appeal to prurient interest; portray sexual conduct in a patently offensive way in light of contemporary community standards; and lack serious artistic, political or scientific value. A 1986 report by Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s pornography commission linked hard-core pornography to sex crimes. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> restated that view Friday when asked by reporters whether the material had actually caused any harm. `` I think it's an accepted fact that the depiction of explicit sex acts ... has the effect of conditioning individuals to committing those acts and conditioning society so that that is accepted as the norm,'' he said. But <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON>, legislative counsel for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, denounced that view as `` hysteria'' and said it conflicted with the First Amendment guaranteeing the right of free speech. `` There is n't any evidence that links adults looking at pornography to any real crime,'' he said in an interview later. `` It may be grotesque, but much of the stuff is just obviously consenting adults having sex.'' <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said the targeted material depicts sexual acts, `` often in a context of violence toward women and children, and often stressing themes such as rape, incest, torture, bondage, child sexual abuse and bestiality.'' The officials displayed at the news conference samples of the advertisements, which included one promoting nine `` full-length movies'' for $ 79 featuring `` 12 hours of the rawest sex ever filmed.'' Another advertised `` new bondage videos,'' including `` Captive Co-Eds'' and `` Harem Girls in Bondage.'' Undercover agents responding to complaints about the material purchased samples and compiled evidence to search 11 companies, and then developed evidence on others, officials said. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said the companies represent `` as much as three-fourths of mailings of sexually oriented material in this country.'' The companies charged operated under a variety of names and had a number of other associated companies. Indictments or criminal complaints were returned in <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Harrisburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Tallahassee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>; and <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash </LOCATION>. The criminal charges were filed in the city where the obscene material was received, not necessarily where the distributors operated.
