<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A World War II veteran paralyzed from the chest down left Friday on a solo, 4,669-mile trans-Atlantic flight to the <LOCATION> German </LOCATION> battlefield where he was wounded in World War II. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>, a 63-year-old real estate company owner and bank chairman in suburban <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION>, took off from <LOCATION> DeKalb-Peachtree </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> about 9:30 a.m. Friday in a single-engine <ORGANIZATION> Cherokee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Piper </ORGANIZATION> equipped with hand controls. He is scheduled to arrive at <LOCATION> Aachen </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, on July 11 and attend a reception in nearby Stolberg, where he was wounded by a sniper during a battle four days after he landed following the <LOCATION> Normandy </LOCATION> invasion. `` What scares me the most is rolling around in this wheelchair and getting in and out of it,'' he said. `` The easy part is the flying. Once I get on the ground, that's the hard part.'' <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> plans to fly his `` Spirit of Shepherd'' airplane up the <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seaboard </LOCATION> and across <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Sondrestrom </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION>, where he plans to spend the Fourth of July. Flying by visual flight rules about 2,000 feet above the ground, <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> then will cross the <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION> ice cap and go on to <LOCATION> Reykjavik </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Bagar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Faeroe </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Stornoway </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Biggin </LOCATION> <LOCATI