<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> says the government will likely extend `` a helping hand'' to drought-stricken farmers as soon as there's a solid assessment of crop damage. But <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said despite stark evidence of the havoc wreaked by the dry spell, `` I think it would be premature to start putting dollars up there.'' After briefing President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on the findings of an interagency task force on the drought, the secretary told reporters Friday that long-range weather forecasts are discouraging. `` We did have some showers in the last few days that helped in some places and the weather's cooler, so those are good signs,'' he said, `` but the weather forecasts indicate that it -LRB- the drought -RRB- has not broken and is continuing and is still very, very serious.'' Meanwhile, it was disclosed by a senior administration official that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will fly to <LOCATION> Davenport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, July 14 to view drought damage. <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON>, who heads a drought-relief task force <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> set up last month, said that `` sooner or later I suspect that the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the administration will see that we need to help with money if the thing continues as bad as it's been. Just how you do that is very complex.'' <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> would not speculate on whether aid money might be available from the roughly $ 17 billion in the commodity price support payments the administration requested for the new budget year starting Oct. 1. There had been indications that because of the drought, not all of the $ 17 billion would be needed for subsidies and that the excess money might be used for aid purposes. `` To get into writing checks to farmers for relief to help tide them over almost needs to await the normal harvest period so that they can compare what they are harvesting, what happened to them,'' he said. `` At that time, we should be standing there with a helping hand.'' It was the fourth briefing that <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> has given <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who established the task force in mid-June to recommend steps the government can take.
