<HEAD>Tamil Sources Say Negotiations Stalled</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS two grafs after 13th, `Neither the...' to UPDATE with
deaths. Pick up 14th pvs, `The Tamil...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tamil militants in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> are ready to surrender, but negotiations have stalled because the rebels are demanding $ 38.4 million from the Indian government, Tamil sources said. Sources close to the rebels in <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Friday the militants were not willing to allow monitoring of how the money was spent. In the southern Indian city of <LOCATION> Madras </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Sadasivam </PERSON> <PERSON> Krishnakumar </PERSON>, a senior member of the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eelam </ORGANIZATION>, was quoted as saying the group was willing to surrender but awaited final orders from its commander. The <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION>, the largest rebel group in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, have been at the forefront of the five-year guerrilla war with the ethnic Sinhalese-dominated government for an independent Tamil homeland. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, which has 50,000 peacekeeping troops in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, has been trying to negotiate an end to the separatist war in the neighboring island nation. The Sri Lankan government on Thursday offered amnesty to the rebels and promised to conduct provincial elections by the end of July in northern and eastern <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, where the rebels want a separate homeland. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Krishnakumar </PERSON> as telling reporters in <LOCATION> Madras </LOCATION> that the <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> would participate in the provincial elections. But he said no decision had been made on whether the <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION>' organization would participate in the elections itself or would form a new political party, the news agency It quoted <PERSON> Krishnakumar </PERSON> as saying the <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> would hand over their weapons as soon as an agreement was reached on the timing of a surrender and the number of arms to be given up. He also said a final decision would be taken only after consultations with the <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION>' commander, <PERSON> Velupillai </PERSON> <PERSON> Prabhakaran </PERSON>. <PERSON> Prabhakaran </PERSON> is based in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> and has successfully eluded a series of manhunts by Indian troops. Last July 29, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> signed a peace accord aimed at ending the ethnic warfare in the island nation off <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s southern coast. The <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> accepted the accord but reneged in October. The accord was accompanied by a payment of $ 384,600 by the Indian government to the rebels for rehabilitation of people affected by the fighting. Since October, more than 400 Indian soldiers have been killed in ambushes and battles with the Tamil rebels, according to the Indian government. Neither the Indians nor the Tamils have estimated the number of rebel deaths. In the latest reported violence, seven Indian soldiers were killed in two ambushes Thursday, said Sri Lankan military officials who spoke on condition of anonymity. They said four were killed near <LOCATION> Trincomalee </LOCATION>, 150 miles north of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>; and three were killed near <LOCATION> Vavuniya </LOCATION>, 110 miles north of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. Two Tamils were killed in <LOCATION> Vavuniya </LOCATION> during search operations launched Friday by the Indians, the officials said. The Tamil insurgency grew out of the belief the community was being discriminated against by the Sinhalese ethnic majority, which controls the country's government and armed forces. Tamils comprise 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people and the Sinhalese form 75 percent. Most Tamils are Hindus, like the majority of Indians, while most Sinhalese are Buddhists. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> became involved in the Sri Lankan ethnic strife because of the sympathies of its own 60 million Tamils to the rebel cause.
