<SECOND>PM-Brazil-Constitution,0715</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Brazil Steeps its New Constitution in Controversy
^By JORGE MEDEROS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 National lawmakers are preparing for final voting on the draft of a new constitution that would reject sweeping land reform but liberalize work rules and end foreign control of mining. The new charter for <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s largest country would also give President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> and his successors a five-year term, a victory for the national leader. The proposed document was born in five months of heated debate in the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, doubling as a Constitutional Convention. It has come up 235 articles that will be the basis for the eighth constitution in the 166 years of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s independence from <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>. The final round of voting is expected to start near the end of July. But the document appears largely to have assumed its final form because a hefty 280 votes in the 559-member convention would be needed to change it. The convention, made up of representatives and senators picked in free elections in 1986, began rewriting the current constitution, dictated during a 1964-1985 military regime, in February 1987. The project started with a computer-generated document touching nearly every aspect of life imaginable in this country of about 140 million people. It then progressed to a first draft of more than 3,000 articles, which critics derided as an `` encyclopedia.'' The real paring began last February with article-by-article voting, in which a majority of 280 was needed for approval. Lawmakers debated vociferously, sometimes violently, especially about issues like land reform, workers' rights and the role of foreign capital. Other hotly contested matters involved how long <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>, the civilian who assumed office in 1985, should stay there; and whether <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> should have a U.S.-type presidential form of government or a European-style prime minister system. As it stands, the proposed constitution contains these provisions: _ <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> and future presidents will serve for five years, compared to the six years of former military presidents. The presidential system remains in place. _ Wide-ranging land reform, in a country where 4 percent of the people own 50 percent of the farmable land, was rejected. _ Workers appear headed for a shorter work week and more liberal vacation benefits. But a liberal maternity leave program might not survive the final vote because businesses view it as too expensive. _ Foreign companies involved in mining will have to leave <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> in four years or transfer financial control to residents of the country. _ Risk contracts allowing foreign companies to drill for oil probably wo n't be continued. _ The return of legalized casino gambling was rejected. The biggest fight broke out between <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> and convention members over the length of the presidential term. <PERSON> Tancredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Neves </PERSON>, a moderate who said he wanted only four years as president before holding elections, died before taking office in 1985. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s last presidential election was in 1960. <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>, vice president-elect and former chief of the military regime's official party, moved into the presidency. He made it clear he believed he had inherited the six-year term of his military predecessor, Gen. <PERSON> Joao </PERSON> <PERSON> Figueiredo </PERSON>, but said he would consider stepping down after five years. However, many congressmen wanted <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> out after four years, with presidential elections in November 1988. <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> won his five years in the constitutional debating, but at the cost of splitting his <ORGANIZATION> Brazilian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> party. Various groups are still seeking changes in the final form of the document. A conservative block, known as the `` Big Center,'' is trying to gain support to strike the anti-foreign articles involving mining and oil prospecting and a proposition allowing civil servants strike under certain circumstances. Leftists, including members of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s two small Communist parties, want to try to knock out conservative provisions on land reform and one that lets civilian powers call in the armed forces to deal with internal problems. There is no time limit for the last round of debate. But Rep. <PERSON> Ulysses </PERSON> <PERSON> Guimaraes </PERSON>, speaker of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and president of the constitutional convention, says he would like officially to proclaim the new constitution on Sept. 7, the national holiday that commemmorates independence.
</TEXT>
