<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> plans to continue a $ 20 million artificial heart research program that had been scheduled to be shelved in the fall, according to <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and administration officials. The reversal means that research contracts at centers in six states wo n't be halted at the end of September, but rather will continue for about 5 -LCB- years as originally planned. The program's goal is to develop a totally implantable electric heart The National Heart, Lung and <ORGANIZATION> Blood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, part of <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION>, said in May that it was suspending the program at the end of the fiscal year and shifting its focus instead to developing a left ventricular assist device, which would help a diseased heart pump blood. The decision provoked an outcry from senators in the states where the research centers are located. They called the decision `` an alarming U-turn'' and said the artificial heart program was a key component of the nation's leadership in biotechnology. Sens. <PERSON> Orrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Utah </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., had threatened in a letter to insert an amendment into an appropriations bill to compel the heart, lung and blood institute to continue the contracts prior to undertaking new obligations Word that the contracts were being revived first came from <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, who relayed the news to a <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> center with a $ 5.5 million contract at stake. `` We heard and confirmed that the contract had been reinstated as of the end of the fiscal year, so that there will be no -LRB- funding -RRB- break,'' <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Bliss </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Biomedical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> said in a telephone interview Friday `` It was originally announced by Senator <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> and confirmed through our contacts at <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Bliss </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Deseret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> that he was told by <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenfant </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION> institute, that artificial heart funding was being restored. <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> called the decision `` good news for the millions who will need artificial hearts or their components.'' There has been no announcement yet by <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION> that the program is being resumed. However, an <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION> official speaking on condition of anonymity said, `` The practicality is that a decision has been made'' and that an announcement was expected as soon as next week. The official stressed that the decision was not just a quick fix, and that it was anticipated that the program would continue as originally planned. Besides the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION>, the other centers conducting the research are the <ORGANIZATION> Hershey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Abiomed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Danvers </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCAT