<HEAD>Police-Rebel Shootout on Bus Kills Three</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Maoist guerrillas and police fought a gunbattle aboard an interstate bus carrying 80 passengers, killing three people, police said. A policeman, a Shining Path rebel and a bus passenger were killed and another policeman was wounded in Friday's shootout, police said. The violence occurred before dawn on <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s major coastal route near <LOCATION> Pisco </LOCATION>, 135 miles south of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>. The bus was traveling along the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> to <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Ica </LOCATION>, 180 miles south. Police said six Shining Path guerrillas forced the privately owned bus to stop by firing machine guns into the air and boarded the vehicle, demanding to see the passengers' papers. The bus riders dived for cover behind their seats as two policemen passengers opened fire. The rebels fired back and fled moments later. Maoist guerrillas frequently halt buses and steal passengers' valuables as an `` insurgency tax. The rebels normally check documents and kill any police or government officials they find. The government says nearly 600 policemen have been among the more than 10,000 people slain in violence related to the Shining Path's eight-year fight to impose Marxist rule in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>.
