<HEAD>Popular Brazilian Television Star Was Known for Wild Antics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE HANDLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Abelardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbosa </PERSON>, a free-wheeling comic who liked to say his goal was to confuse everything but who worked to forge a distinctly Brazilian style of television, died of a heart attack. He was 70. <PERSON> Barbosa </PERSON>, known on his amateur hour as `` Chacrinha,'' or barnyard in <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION>, succumbed at his home in <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Janeiro </LOCATION> late Thursday, his family announced Friday. He had been ill for several months. His body lay in state Friday at <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hall </LOCATION>, where hundreds of fans and well-wishers, mostly poor, lined up to pay respects. Riot police took positions outside to prevent any emotional tumult among mourners. The entertainer was born in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s poor northeast region and graduated from medical school there. But he never practiced as a doctor, gravitating in the 1940s to <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Janeiro </LOCATION> and radio. He became a disc jockey and emcee. The entertainer delighted generations of Brazilian radio and television fans with his own brand of unpredictable antics. When television came to <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> in the 1960s, <PERSON> Barbosa </PERSON> became a legend with a amateur show called `` Chacrinha's <PERSON> Horn </PERSON>.'' His nonsense slogans and silly rhymes caught on throughout the country. Media critics said he represented the essence of `` Brazilian-ness'' and prevented television here from turning into an American clone. In a rare serious moment in an interview years ago, <PERSON> Barbosa </PERSON> said he felt he had brought a certain Brazilian originality to television, which he viewed as subject to foreign _ mostly <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> _ influence. On `` Chacrinha's <PERSON> Horn </PERSON>,'' Chacrinha, an overweight man with thick glasses and curly, white hair, generally sported an outlandish outfit making him look like a clown. If he did not appreciate performers, he would honk a horn in their faces and send them away in disgrace, prompting thunderous laughter from the audience. The program also highlighted <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s leading pop music singers and rock groups. Go-go girls gyrated in the background, smoke bombs exploded on stage, and cameras cut crazily from one shot to another with no apparent logic. `` I've come here to confuse everything,'' he often said in nose-tight closeups, and the phrase caught on nationwide. He also delighted fans with such gratuitous behavior as brandishing a pineapple or a slab of dried codfish and taunting the audience: `` Who wants this?'' `` Me, me,'' everyone would shout. `` Well, you ca n't have it. This stuff's expensive,'' he would retort and lob the item out of reach.
