GANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said. On Thursday, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rejected the petition of the three men to drop charges of rebellion and kidnapping. It agreed, however, to place them under the custody of a church group while awaiting trial. In the new charges, the military said the three men were seen with communist <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas in four <LOCATION> Quezon </LOCATION> province towns from May 23 to 25 and on June 2 this year and instructed new rebel recruits, the agency said. Earlier, the military had accused them of taking part in a Feb. 3 raid in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> town in <LOCATION> Quezon </LOCATION> and taking hostage two policemen after the attack. <PERSON> Hermansson </PERSON> has said he arrived in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> for the first time in mid-May, and the other two said they were in the capital on the day of the Feb. 3 raid.
