<BYLINE>By TED M. NATT JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT CAMPBELL, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 No action is warranted against anyone as a result of a collision of two Army helicopters in March, even though pilot error probably caused the accident that killed 17 soldiers, an <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> report says. The accident happened March 8 when a UH-60 Black Hawk returning from a solo instruction flight collided with the lead helicopter in a formation of three returning from a night training mission to pick up soldiers in the field. `` Up to the point of impact, the missions were formed just as briefed,'' said Maj. <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Schoel </PERSON>, public-affairs officer at the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> base. The report found that the collision `` was the result of the two air crews' being unable to see each other in the final moments of flight,'' according to a statement read by <PERSON> Schoel </PERSON> at a news conference Friday. The approximately 175-page report concluded, `` Pilot error, to wit, a reasonable mistake in judgment is the most probable explanation for the cause of this accident.'' But the report, compiled by an investigation board of six <ORGANIZATION> Fort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Campbell </ORGANIZATION> officers _ all aviators, said: `` There should be no action taken against anyone as no foundation for negligence can be established. The accident was not due to lack of diligence, nor unreasonable or unprofessional conduct.'' The investigation board found no evidence of a mechanical malfunction in the two <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hawks </ORGANIZATION> involved in the crash. `` Nor can it be confirmed that there were any procedural errors on the part of either crew,'' <PERSON> Schoel </PERSON> said. The report, however, cited other factors, including exterior and interior design characteristics of the UH-60 <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hawks </ORGANIZATION> and limited pilot training using night-vision goggles. The report noted a lack of lighting on the helicopters, and said the number and the size of position lights on the outside of the $ 4.6 million Black Hawk were inadequate. The helicopters were made by <ORGANIZATION> Sikorsky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> division of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said Staff Sgt. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> of the public information office at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Campbell </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Stratford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, late Friday, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stangrone </PERSON>, a Sikorsky spokesman, said: `` All aircraft have some degree of field-of-view limitation. Obviously, the ideal cockpit is a glass bubble with an unobstructed view. It's a matter of design tradeoffs that consider structural integrity, ballistic tolerance, survivability and so on. ... Design and operational tradeoffs also determine the extent and intensity of exterior aircraft lighting.'' The report said one of the two helicopters may not have had its anti-collision strobe light turned on as required at the time of the accident. `` That's the only item in question _ the strobe light,'' <PERSON> Schoel </PERSON> said. The lead helicopter, struck broadside, carried 13 soldiers. The other craft carried four. All 17 victims belonged to the 101st Airborne Division at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Campbell </LOCATION>. The other two helicopters landed safely.
