<HEAD>Gulf Salt Water Threatens New Orleans River Water</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Corrects saltwater to salt water thruout, except where
adjectival</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALBERTO S. FRANCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A wedge of salt water creeping up the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> could begin tainting <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>' water supply in a week despite federal efforts to build a dike to slow the intrusion, a university professor says. The salt water from the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, flowing upstream because the worst drought in decades has weakened the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>'s flow, is traveling about two miles per day and was within 17 miles of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> on Friday. When the salt water first reaches the city, on about July 10, the contamination will be minimal, but by July 20 the salinity of the city's water could hit 200 parts per million, said <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor emeritus <PERSON> Raphael </PERSON> <PERSON> Kazmann </PERSON>. That would make the water drinkable but `` make the coffee taste lousy,'' he said. In addition, the salt water could corrode appliances such as water heaters and dishwashers, he said. By the end of the month, the salinity probably will reach 300 ppm, which is above federal drinking water standards although it can be tolerated by most healthy people, he said. By the end of June the salt water had traveled as far upriver as it had on Oct. 8, 1965, a severe drought year, <PERSON> Kazmann </PERSON> said. The river is usually at its lowest point in the fall, and that does n't bode well for <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> in 1988, he warned. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> began construction Thursday on a $ 947,000 sand and clay barrier that will stretch 1,200 feet along the contours of the river bottom about 63 miles from where the river meets the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Construction is expected to take less than a month, spokesman <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Sossaman </PERSON> said Friday. Salt water hugs the river bottom because it is heavier than fresh water. It is advancing up the river because the drought-induced low flow is not rapid enough to push it back to the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. The upper point of the saltwater wedge is about 15 miles past the dike the Corps is building, <PERSON> Sossaman </PERSON> said. `` The levee is not as good an idea as it was before,'' said <PERSON> Frederic </PERSON> <PERSON> Chatry </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>' Engineering Division. `` But we're not trying to solve the saltwater intrusion problem. We're just trying to mitigate the part of saltwater intrusion caused because we deepened <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pass </ORGANIZATION> 5 feet ... last fall and winter. <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pass </LOCATION> is a primary navigation channel for entering the river from the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. To compensate for the salt water's movement and to make up for lost time, the Corps might build the sand and clay sill slightly higher than originally planned, <PERSON> Chatry </PERSON> said. Residents of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> and the several other communities who get their drinking water from the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> should n't panic, <PERSON> Sossaman </PERSON> said At first, the salt water will not perceptibly change the taste of the city's water supply, he said. If the salinity increases, it should only pose problems for those under salt-restrictive diets. So far, abnormal salinity has not registered at the city's water intakes, said Sewerage and <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Puglia </PERSON>. The board is working with the state and the <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> but has no citywide plan, he said. Saltwater intrusion in the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> is not uncommon, <PERSON> Sossaman </PERSON> noted. Communities close to the Gulf of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> experience the problem every summer with varying degrees of severity. `` Because of the drought, this summer it will probably go up higher and stay longer,'' he said, adding it could go as far as 75 miles upstream to <LOCATION> Baton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rouge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La </LOCATION>. Autumn rains should help force the salt water back to the Gulf, he said.
