<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Karoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> has appealed for talks with <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> following heightened tensions between the two <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> allies, a government newspaper reported today. In an interview with the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Magyar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hirlap </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> was quoted as stressing the `` political necessity and moral obligation'' for direct talks with <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> to find an end to the dispute. The newspaper said <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>, who also is premier, wants to go to <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> for talks but did not know when. <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> was quoted as saying there have been no contacts between he and <LOCATION> Romanian </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Nicolae </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> but considered it important that <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> had called for a meeting between representatives of the two nations to improve relations. On Friday, the <ORGANIZATION> Hungarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> passed a resolution accusing <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> of violating the human rights of ethnic Hungarians and other minorities in the neighboring East-bloc country. The action was taken at the end of a week of escalating tensions over <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>'s planned demolition of 7,000 villages with the residents to be resettled in `` agro-industrial'' centers. <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> newspapers said some Hungarians were being prevented from entering <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>. The resolution adopted by <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> with only one abstention said <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> is violating `` the fundamental human, national and nationalities-related rights.'' It called on <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> to re-examine its resettlement plan. There are about 1.7 million ethnic Hungarians living in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> and about 220,000 ethnic Germans as well as thousands of Serbs. Most of the Hungarians live in <LOCATION> Transylvania </LOCATION>, many in villages to be destroyed. <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> claims the resettlement will provide higher living standards and gain productive agricultural land where houses now stand. `` The annihilation of the values of the settlements doomed to destruction ... would mean an irreparable loss not only to the Hungarian, German and other ethnic minorities, but also to the Romanian people themselves,'' the resolution said. Earlier this week <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> expelled several Hungarian diplomats from an area inhabited by many ethnic Hungarians, closed a Hungarian consulate in <LOCATION> Cluj </LOCATION> and began turning back Hungarian tourists. <PERSON> Matyas </PERSON> <PERSON> Szueroes </PERSON>, the head of the foreign relations committee who presented the resolution to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, said <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s leadership would `` always be cooperating partners'' and was prepared to go ahead with preparations for a meeting of the two countries' premiers Hungarian newspapers quoted officials and travelers as saying Hungarians wishing to enter <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> were being turned back at the border. In some cases only those traveling through <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> to other destinations were allowed to cross into the country, the papers said. <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>'s decision to close the Hungarian consulate in <LOCATION> Cluj </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Traynsylvania </LOCATION> followed a demonstration by some 50,000 people who marched past the <ORGANIZATION> Romanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> to protest the resettlement plan.
