<FIRST>r p AM-AttackingTheBase Bjt   07-02 0832</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Attacking The Base, Bjt,820</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Bush: Looking for Votes In All The `Wrong' Places?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In recent days, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaigned in <LOCATION> Mississipi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, states that have backed a Democratic presidential hopeful only once in 28 years. This week, Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is going to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' hometown for a Greek Orthodox church dinner. No, these presidential candidates are n't just wasting their time, looking for votes in all the wrong places. These events are early feints in the general election campaign, a strategy called attacking your opponent's base. It is one piece of putting together the <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> puzzle to win 270 electoral votes and the White House on Nov. 8. `` If <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is tied down in places like <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>, he's going to have a hard time doing what he needs to win the election,'' said Democratic pollster <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Mellman </PERSON>. `` It's a smart strategy for both sides,'' said <PERSON> Vince </PERSON> <PERSON> Breglio </PERSON>, a Republican campaign tactician. `` It's not defending your solid core vote. It's the marginal voters who are part of your base. They are part of the core, but not a dependable part.'' Of course, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> are looking for every possible vote in the fall. The theory behind the `` attacking the base'' strategy is straightforward: If a candidate must spend his time making certain the people who usually vote for his party will back him, he wo n't have time to win the swing voters who have been increasingly crucial to victory in this country For example, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has campaigned across the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> and the farm belt in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, regions that have been very strong for the Republicans. Thus, if <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> must defend his base of support in those areas, he will have less time to campaign in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, where the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> needs to do well. While such a strategy is used in all kinds of races, it is particularly important in a presidential campaign because of the <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> system. Winning the most votes does n't mean winning the White House. A candidate must win enough states to gain a majority of the 538 electoral votes at stake to succeed <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in 1989. Of course, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and their aides proclaim that they will battle for every state in the fall, taking nothing for granted and conceding nothing. `` It's not designed to make <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> pay attention to his base,'' said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodin </PERSON> of the Thursday trip to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. `` It's an indication that we are not going to take anything for granted.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Dach </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor's strength and campaigning all across the country makes it tough for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and the GOP `` In their grand plan, they thought they did n't have to secure landing rights in big regions of the country,'' <PERSON> Dach </PERSON> said. `` Now, they're finding they have to lease apartments everywhere.'' The reality is that there are limited resources for a presidential campaign and limited time for a candidate's campaigning `` Once things have started to solidify, I'm sure the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign will sit down and make a careful assessment of where to concentrate the resources,'' <PERSON> Mellman </PERSON> said. The starting point of any <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> strategy _ and the `` attacking the base'' tactic _ is history. And history is on the side of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and the Republicans. One way to look at electoral history is the percentage of the two-party vote for each candidate from 1952 through 1984. <PERSON> Mellman </PERSON> points out that <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> have averaged a majority of the vote in only six states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> over that period. That's a total of 52 electoral votes from <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>. The Republicans have averaged at least 55 percent of the vote in 27 states through the same elections, for 208 electoral votes. Thus, Democrats would have to win 218 electoral votes among the 17 remaining states to add to their base to return to power in the White House. The <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> could hold onto its historic base and win the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> with only 62 electoral votes from the 278 available in those swing states. But <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> aides say the appeal to history is a misleading one, saying the Republican spokesmen are `` trying to erect a historical barrier between <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and the voters.'' Democrats point to such states as <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> _ a traditionally <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> state _ where <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has a substantial lead in the polls. In addition, a purely regional strategy is tough to pull off, as differences between the regions shrink and the influence of national television coverage grows. `` The best thing to do is cherry-pick,'' <PERSON> Mellman </PERSON> says, `` taking a state here in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>, and one there.'' With the national polls moving dramatically in recent weeks, <PERSON> Breglio </PERSON> agrees that the fall campaign is going to be `` hand-to-hand, state-by-state'' combat as <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> try for the magic majority of 270 electoral votes.
</TEXT>
