 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Democratic leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> on Saturday both offered the same election-year Fourth of July advice for Americans: Vote. `` It's up to each of us to preserve, protect and defend <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s precious heritage,'' the president said in his weekly radio address. `` Some of us have done just that on the battlefield. But all of us can do it each and every day. `` We can vote at election time. We can volunteer to help political campaigns for the candidates of our choice, as well as volunteer for work that's needed around our community. And we can simply raise our children well, do our jobs well and live in God's light. <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> majority leader from <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, said in the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> response to the president's speech that Independence Day in 1988 `` is different because this year we must choose a new path for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' `` This is an election year,'' <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said. `` We are about to choose a new president.'' `` Celebrate your freedom in the most meaningful way this year,'' he said. `` Participate. Exercise that most important uniquely American privilege. Vote.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> spoke from Camp <PERSON> David </PERSON>, the presidential retreat in the <LOCATION> Catoctin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, where he and first lady <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> are spending the weekend. The <ORGANIZATION> Reagans </ORGANIZATION> will return to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Monday and watch the traditional capital fireworks show from a balcony of the White House.
