<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Blast Outside Stadium Kills Two, Injures 26</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with two confirmed dead, 26
hurt, other detail; picks up 5th pvs: Sportswriters covering...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A car bomb exploded today outside a crowded <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> sports stadium, killing at least two people and injuring 26, police said. The blast occurred on a street alongside <LOCATION> Ellis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> stadium minutes after the end of the rugby match between <LOCATION> Transvaal </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Orange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>, said police spokesman <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Louw </PERSON>. <PERSON> Louw </PERSON> said the two men killed were white. Among the injured, 23 are white, two are black and one is Asian, <PERSON> Louw </PERSON> said. The stadium seats about 75,000 people and is the largest sporting facility in the <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> area. The attendance figure was not immediately available, but Saturday afternoon matches generally attract at least 25,000 fans. Sportswriters covering the match said they saw flames leaping 60 yards into the air following the explosion, the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> reported. They said the blast occurred just outside an entrance gate to the stadium, <ORGANIZATION> SAPA </ORGANIZATION> said. Several surrounding buildings in the downtown area were set ablaze, but were extinguished by firemen within several minutes, witnesses said. Metal from the car that exploded was found up to 200 yards away from the blast, witnesses added. Several additional cars also were damaged they said. Police immediately blocked off the area and began checking nearby parked cars for additional explosives. Rugby is the most popular team sport among white South Africans, and tens of thousands of whites regularly attend weekend matches at <LOCATION> Ellis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>. The bombing was the latest in a recent series of attacks aimed at civilian targets. There have been more than 90 bombings since the government declared a natinwide state of emergency in June 1986, including some 25 this year. Police have blamed virtually all the attacks on the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> guerrilla group, the main black organization attempting to overthrow the white-led government. The group, based in <LOCATION> Lusaka </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION>, seldom confirms or denies involvement in specific attacks. However, recent statements by <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> leaders have suggested that the organization approves of attacks on civilian targets. On Thursday, 13 whites and one black were hurt by a bomb that exploded outside a fast food restaurant in a <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> shopping center at the Poyntons Building, which houses the air force and prison service headquarters on upper floors. Hospital officials said none was hurt seriously. Two of the injured people were children. The country is run under a system of apartheid, a policy of segregation that preserves power and privilege for <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s 5 million whites and denies rights and a voice in national affairs to its 26 million blacks. On Friday, the government proposed tough measures to enforce residential segregation, and critics said it could mean mass eviction of blacks from white areas. The bills are to be debated in August. The government has not strictly enforced the 35-year-old act Group Areas Act in recent years, which restricts blacks to certain areas. The proposed amendment to the act calls for the hiring of inspectors to check violations of the law. It would make it easier for authorities to confiscate property and to evict and prosecute people living in areas not designated for their race group. On June 10, President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> extended for a third year the country's state of emergency.
