<HEAD>Controversial Dukakis Prison Siting Enters Presidential Politics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW BRAINTREE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 On a hilltop overlooking this tiny town is what Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> believes is the perfect site for a new prison and what opponents of that plan say is the centerpiece of a corrupt land deal. The 782 acres in rural <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Braintree </LOCATION>, home of a defunct religious academy and perhaps a future prison, is the battlefield for a two-year war over the prison plans that is intensifying as the state moves to buy the property and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, now the certain Democratic presidential nominee, eyes the White House. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> spent much of 1986 defending his choice of the site and was drawn back into the fray last month, when the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> acknowledged it was conducting a preliminary inquiry into allegations by prison opponents that developers who bought the property for $ 3.2 million and quickly offered it to the state for $ 9.5 million were given inside information about the plans. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> said was not a subject of the investigation, and administration officials have flatly rejected allegations there were improper deals and suggested prison opponents sharpened their attack to get attention during the presidential campaign. `` I do n't have any interest in that,'' insists <PERSON> Dorothea </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas-Vitrac </PERSON>, the vocal leader of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Braintree </LOCATION>'s opposition group _ <ORGANIZATION> Conserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Our </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Small </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Town </ORGANIZATION>. `` We are going after our sitting governor, not after a presidential candidate.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' Republican opponent in the fall election, Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, has steered clear of the controversy. `` Given the fact that it is under some kind of investigation, we would have no comment,'' said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spokewoman <PERSON> Alix </PERSON> <PERSON> Glen </PERSON>. But it has drawn national attention because it involves a central element of the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> candidacy _ a pledge to bring integrity and competence to the White House _ and offers a glimpse at his handling of a complex and controversial issue. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> named the site for a prison in 1986 and opponents, who had organized when the state first considered the land two years earlier, complained that a facility for 500 inmates and several hundred staff members would overwhelm the town of barely 800 people. <PERSON> Thomas-Vitrac </PERSON> concedes opponents have no hard evidence that the developers were tipped off but contends there `` have to be smoking guns'' among more than 100 documents <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> refuses to make public, citing executive privilege. `` The governor, for reasons known only to him, has lied about his knowledge of this siting,'' <PERSON> Thomas-Vitrac </PERSON> said last week. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has repeatedly said he did not know who owned the land when he picked it and requested up to $ 10 million to buy it. Notes of an administration aide appear to show one of the developers names came up twice during a meeting with prison opponents in <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' office, but the governor has said he does not recall that and aides have said the name was mentioned only is passing. `` The bottom line is that this is a ` not in my backyard issue' and the rest of it is frankly nonsense,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Circo </PERSON>, a former <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> aide who handled the project `` You'd have to have been in an igloo somewhere to not know we were looking for prison space across the state and that <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Braintree </LOCATION> was one.'' <PERSON> Thomas-Vitrac </PERSON> contends the withheld documents contain some reference to developers <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Striar </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON>. The town had an agreement with the Seventh Day Adventists Church that the land would not be sold for a project not in the town's interests. <PERSON> Thomas-Vitrac </PERSON> contends <PERSON> Striar </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON> were <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> allies used to serve as middlemen so the state could get the land without a fight and reward the developers would with a triple return on their investment. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> denies any deal took place and has said he met <PERSON> Striar </PERSON> only once. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Republicans have been distributing a photo of that meeting _ on a crowded platform during a 1986 groundbreaking for a community center named for <PERSON> Striar </PERSON>'s parents. <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON> grew up in the same neighborhood as <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and has donated to his campaigns, but both men said they are nothing more than casual acquaintances. <PERSON> Striar </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON> say they learned of the state's interest through their broker and that they only considered selling to the state after local officials rejected their plans to build a psychiatric hospital. An unlikely <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> defender, Republican <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON>, said Thurday that he confirmed publicly that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was not under investigation `` because I felt it was necessary to respond to the gossip, innuendo and smear that might sully an otherwise unsullied reputation.'' Two appraisals estimate the site's worth between $ 5 million and $ 6 million, according to three <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> administration aides, all of whom requested anonymity. A third appraisal will be completed this week. Negotiations with <PERSON> Striar </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON> then will begin, and the state plans to offer much less than the $ 9.5 million sought by the owners two years ago. The two sides may end up in court if no agreement is reached and the state seeks to take to land by emminent domain.
