<HEAD>Danish Formula' Suggested for Ending ANZUS Nuclear Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials say <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> may be able to restore military cooperation with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> with a formula similar to that which keeps anti-nuclear <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> in the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. The subject came up after both <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Australian leaders voiced regret here the past week at the absence of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> from the third straight annual ministerial meeting of <ORGANIZATION> ANZUS </ORGANIZATION>, the military alliance formed by the three <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> countries after World War II. <LOCATION> U.S.-New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> military ties deteriorated after Prime Minister <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lange </PERSON> in 1985 barred a visiting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warship under his new <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> government's decision to close <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> territory to nuclear-armed ships. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> later read <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> out of <ORGANIZATION> ANZUS </ORGANIZATION> in order to protect its policy of refusing to confirm or deny whether any ship carries nuclear weapons. `` There must be a formula, if <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> would only look for it, that would make it possible for them to come back into the fold,'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> told reporters last Wednesday after a two-day meeting with Australian leaders. Asked to elaborate on <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s remark, another high <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official told reporters Friday, `` One formula they might look at, I suppose, is the Danish formula.'' Another <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official described the Danish formula as `` informing their allies by letter that <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> does not permit calls at their ports by ships armed with nuclear weapons and leave it at that.'' The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials spoke on condition they not be identified. <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> have announced settlement of a dispute similar to the <LOCATION> U.S.-New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> controversy that erupted when the <ORGANIZATION> Danish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> in April adopted a resolution requiring the government to notify visiting warships of <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s 31-year-old ban on nuclear weapons. After new, but inconclusive, elections waged partly on the issue, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s coalition prime minister, <PERSON> Poul </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON>, told the <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> on June 7 that allied governments had been informed of <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s general policy banning atomic weapons during peacetime, and that in cases of specific ship visits foreign governments would be told that <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> assumes the visit is in compliance with Danish rules. `` The government considers that this procedure respects both the Danish non-nuclear policy and the views of our allies,'' <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said June 7 the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had noted the prime minister's statement and one by Danish Foreign Minister <PERSON> Uffe </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellemann-Jensen </PERSON> that the formula `` respects the policy of our allies neither to confirm nor to deny the presence of nuclear weapons on their naval vessels.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have said a similar arrangement is used on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> port visits to <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> has not recently suggested using the Danish formula and it would be up to it to take the initiative on the matter, said one of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials. Prime Minister <PERSON> Lange </PERSON> in the past has likened <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>'s nuclear ban to those of the Scandinavian <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies.
