Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> had publicly endorsed <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>'s nomination, but some of its 35 lawmakers voted against <PERSON> Chung </PERSON>. The top judiciary post has been vacant since June 17 when <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Yong-chul </PERSON> resigned under pressure from junior judges demanding democratic reforms in the judiciary. Under the new constitution adopted last year, <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> needed approval from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> to stay in the post. Hundreds of judges demanded his resignation, criticizing him for his alleged pro-government role in the past. The failure of <PERSON> Chung </PERSON>'s nomination to pass parliament will strain relations between the governing and opposition camps and will be difficult for <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> to handle, according to political analysts. Also Saturday, the Assembly approved former lawyer <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Young-jun </PERSON> as the chief government auditor. The nomination was passed by 154-10, with 131 absentions and one invalid vote.
