<HEAD>Tawana Brawley: Lost in the Shuffle</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note language in 11th graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As the <PERSON> Tawana </PERSON> <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON> case becomes ever more complicated, the focus has shifted from the black teen-ager to her three advisers and their racial politics. And the crucial question _ What happened when she disappeared for four days last year? _ has been obscured. Although she has maintained an almost complete public silence, <PERSON> Tawana </PERSON> <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON> is famous. She has made the cover of People magazine and was the subject of a `` Donahue'' program. Her picture is all over the newspapers, whether she attends the theater on the arm of an adviser or visits the church where her mother has sought sanctuary. But the <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON> case has become less and less about Miss <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON> and more and more about the tactics and motives of her publicist, the Rev. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharpton </PERSON>, and her lawyers, <PERSON> Alton </PERSON> <PERSON> Maddox </PERSON> and <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>. Miss <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON> disappeared from her home in <LOCATION> Wappingers </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, for four days last November. She was found in a garbage bag, her hair cut and her body smeared with excrement and marked with racial slurs. She has said she was abducted and sexually molested by six white men, one of whom had a badge, but questions have been raised about her story, including suggestions that <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON> was at a party during part of the time she was missing. Her mother, <PERSON> Glenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON>, has said that the family initially cooperated with authorities, but they stopped assisting after she and the advisers felt that local and state officials were trying to protect the guilty. The advisers say that the <PERSON> Tawana </PERSON> <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON> case illustrates how the state's criminal justice system consistently discriminates against blacks. The case has been unorthodox from the start, but in recent weeks a series of bizarre developments has diverted attention from the alleged victim to those around her. First, since the teen-ager would not talk, investigators subpoenaed her mother to testify before a grand jury. Rather than cooperate, she sought sanctuary in a church in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>'s black Bedford-Stuyvesant section. <PERSON> Sharpton </PERSON> challenged the special prosecutor, state Attorney General <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON>, to arrest her and `` show the nation the moral beast you are.'' <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> stayed put, and so did <PERSON> Glenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON>. That was when <PERSON> Sharpton </PERSON> aide <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> <PERSON> McKinnon </PERSON> defected. He charged that <PERSON> Sharpton </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> and <PERSON> Maddox </PERSON>, in fact, had no evidence that would shed light on what happened to Miss <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON>, and that they were using her case to fuel a political movement. He quoted <PERSON> Sharpton </PERSON> as saying the case could make the advisers `` the biggest niggers in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> McKinnon </PERSON> characterized the <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON> advisers' claim to evidence of what really happened `` a pack of lies,'' and said, `` The <PERSON> Tawana </PERSON> <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON> story may be that there is no <PERSON> Tawana </PERSON> <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON> story.'' <PERSON> Sharpton </PERSON> counterattacked, denouncing <PERSON> McKinnon </PERSON> as a gofer who had no access to the Brawleys or their advisers' deliberations. <PERSON> Sharpton </PERSON> also described <PERSON> McKinnon </PERSON> as a killer -LRB- he was a soldier in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> -RRB-, a psychopath -LRB- <PERSON> McKinnon </PERSON> received psychiatric treatment after returning from <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> -RRB- and a bigamist -LRB- <PERSON> McKinnon </PERSON> did not complete divorce proceedings to end his first marriage -RRB-. A week later an unemployed former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> technician, <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> McClease </PERSON>, claimed to have been promised $ 11,000 by <PERSON> Sharpton </PERSON> to bug <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>'s home and office and <PERSON> Sharpton </PERSON>'s home in order to protect <PERSON> Sharpton </PERSON> if the case began to unravel. <PERSON> McClease </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> WCBS-TV </ORGANIZATION> he had tapes that substantiated his allegations, which generally supported <PERSON> McKinnon </PERSON>'s. Polls showed that New Yorkers, including an overwhelming share of whites and a majority of blacks, believed that <PERSON> Glenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON> and her advisers had not handled the case responsibly, and that the latter were lying. But then came another jolt _ the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> said the tapes McClease produced were blank and appeared never to have been used, and charged <PERSON> McClease </PERSON> with obstruction of justice and perjury. Investigators who thought they had seen everything rolled their eyes and shook their heads. <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Greathead </PERSON>, first assistant state attorney general, was more restrained than most, calling the blank tapes `` another unexpected development in a case that has been full of many surprising twists and turns.'' <PERSON> Sharpton </PERSON> was jubilant. `` We are coming to get our deed papers,'' he said, referring to what he said would be a $ 100 million libel suit against <ORGANIZATION> WCBS </ORGANIZATION>. `` We gon na go see what color curtains we want in our new building.'' But the flamboyant preacher also had reason for concern: he reportedly was being investigated by the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZ