<HEAD>With AM-Reagan-Byrd-Fourth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is the text of Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>'s response to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s weekly radio address broadcast Saturday: Good afternoon This is Senator <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. This Monday is the Fourth of July. For most Americans, the Fourth of July is a day to spend with family and friends. We hold picnics, go to the beach, march in parades, and look forward to fireworks at night. We celebrate our freedom. It is a good day to be an American. We share our love of country around the barbecue pit and the picnic table. We take stock of nation's prosperity between innings during the annual softball game. We see the future in the delight of our children as they watch the fireworks light up the sky. It is a day of quite patriotism, reaffirmation, and thankfulness. We thank <PERSON> God </PERSON> for our good fortune that we are Americans. We reaffirm our commitment to the legacy given to us by our forbearers. We pray for those Americans upon whom misfortune has fallen. But, this Fourth is a little different. It is different because this year we must choose a new path for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. This is an election year; we're about to choose a new president. And on this Fourth of July, it is a time for reflection as well as celebration. It is a time to remember what has made <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> great and to use those traditional strengths as we contemplate the future. Our nation has unfinished business. Our foreign competition is still beating us at our own game. Our children are not getting the education they deserve. The <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> dream of owning a home seems to be almost out of reach for the next generation. Drug dealers flood the market with dope and death. The American family, the bedrock of our nation's foundation, is changing and needs new policies to preserve it. What is most disturbing is the erosion of the public trust. Wall Street has been rocked by scandal. Our national security is being endangered by greed. Honesty and integrity seem to be in short supply. For some Americans, those may seem to be reasons enough to turn away from politics, from making a choice about the future. `` Nothing is ever going to change,'' they say. Throwing up their hands in despair, `` Why vote at all?'' But, if this had been the attitude of <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON> and the other great founders of our nation on the first Fourth of July, where would we be today? Let us reject the cynicism that says that things can not be improved. You, the people, have the power to change things and to let those in high places know what you expect. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> has unfinished business. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> was not founded on cynicism. It was founded on hope by strong people who built a new country by making new choices however difficult. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> was built on love of country, belief in the common man, hard and honest work, optimism and religious faith. It is your government, and it can reflect your values. And it can help to solve <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s problem, but you have to participate. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> can deal with its drug problem. American can educate our children better. American can adapt to the changing needs of the family. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> can meet our security commitments without busting the national budget. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> can meet our energy needs. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> can protect the environment. And <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> can demand a fair deal from our trading partners overseas. Americans want a restoration of integrity and common decency. Those are values that we all share and understand. I come from <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, the state where patriotism and family are cherished traditions. I know most other Americans are like that too. I have great faith in this country. When we Americans put our minds to it, we can solve our problems. And Americans are always willing to imagine something new and better for their country. Americans are optimists. This Fourth of July then, let us remember our strengths, our heritage, and our power to determine our own fate. We can give <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> a new beginning. Celebrate your freedom in the most meaningful way this year. Participate. Exercise that most important, uniquely American privilege; register and vote. Get involved.
</TEXT>
