<FIRST>r p AM-LaFollette'sBigHat     07-02 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-La Follette's Big Hat,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sensitive Skin Tough on Politician</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD EGGLESTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Follette </PERSON> tossed his hat in the ring for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, some people wondered why the hat was so big. <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Follette </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>'s secretary of state, wears a gray Australian bush hat almost everywhere he goes. The reason is, he has the same mild form of skin cancer as President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. His wide-brimmed hat is a slight political liability, but also a potential trademark and a tool for educating people about the hazards of excessive exposure to the sun, <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Follette </PERSON> said. `` I do n't wear a hat out of a quirk, I wear a hat for very realistic health reasons,'' <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Follette </ORGANIZATION>, 48, said during a campaign visit at a recent farmers market on Capitol Square. `` I've learned that the sun can be harmful.'' <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Follette </PERSON> is one of five Democrats and two Republicans vying to succeed retiring Sen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, D-Wis. `` It's very sobering, realizing being brown is not as beautiful as you think it is,'' said <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Follette </PERSON>, who was diagnosed three years ago as having basal cell carcinoma, the most common and least dangerous form of skin cancer Nationally, an estimated 300,000 to 400,000 people are diagnosed each year as having the easily treated form of cancer. It is not even counted in official cancer statistics, but still could be fatal if untreated. <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Follette </PERSON>'s case was diagnosed when what he thought was a pimple turned out to be a pre-cancerous spot on his skin. Since then, he has gone in for a checkup every six months. His physician, Dr. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Snow </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, said skin cancer accounts for more than one-third of all cancer cases, and as many skin cancers are diagnosed annually as cancers of the lung, breast, colon and prostate combined. `` It's all related to sunlight,'' Snow said. `` It's a totally preventable problem, but since when has the average person ever been rational?'' Dr. <PERSON> Derek </PERSON> <PERSON> Cripps </PERSON>, also of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION>, recommends that everyone wear sun screen with a protection factor of 15 or higher; <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Follette </ORGANIZATION> wears sun screen rated 32 as well as his wide-brimmed hat. Wearing a hat puts off some people, <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Follette </PERSON> said. `` You ca n't be a hermit; the hat is my solution,'' <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Follette </ORGANIZATION> said. `` The big brim is important because it keeps the sun off my nose and ears.''
</TEXT>
