<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Conference     07-02 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Conference,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party to Review Credentials of Its 20 Million Members</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> will review the qualifications of each of its 20 million members before the end of the year, a move that could help strengthen <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s political base. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> directed that the examination of party members be conducted in the open and not `` through discussion behind the scenes,'' the official <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Pravda </ORGANIZATION> said Saturday. The four-day <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> conference that ended Friday approved a call for reevaluating party membership as well as backing <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s program for a stronger legislature, presidency and a 10-year limit on the terms of party and government officials. Pravda said the conference considered it necessary `` to carry out this year a ... campaign in party organizations, governed by the decisions of the conference about reform of the political system, democratization of party life.'' Such a reevaluation of party membership could become a widespread effort to force opponents of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms out of the party, but it is more likely to be targeted against the idle and corrupt. `` Not a single honest man should be left outside perestroika,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said in his speech opening the conference Tuesday. But the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief also has said that the criterion for judging party members is their attitude toward his reform effort. A limited housecleaning could be expected to strengthen <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> by eliminating some of the most intransigent opponents of reform and improving the party's effectiveness. And it could improve the image of the party, which the policy-making <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> criticized before the conference as having a bureaucratic stranglehold on the economy and government. Communists must go through a lengthy selection process and ideological training before being granted membership in the party, a prerequisite for advancement to positions of responsibility in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> society. About one of 10 Soviet adults is a member of the party. Although conference delegates backed the review of the membership roll, it is unlikely they would have gone along with a widespread campaign against conservatives. Many of the speeches to the conference struck a tone considerably more conservative than <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s, and the official press said before the conference that mid-level party officials had rammed through slates of delegates despite <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s call for an open, democratic election procedure. The resolution calling for the review of party membership also called for a a division of power between the party apparatus and local governing councils, or soviets. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> proposed at the conference to get the party out of day-to-day management of affairs and leave that to responsible government officials and plant managers. The resolution was the only one of seven from the party conference published by the Soviet press Saturday, and it was uncertain when the rest of the resolutions would be released. The conference of 5,000 Communists from around the country, called to review progress on <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms and chart a course for the future, acted on the party review at the urging of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has told party bureaucrats they must either get behind him or get out of the way. But he said the party still must give its members a chance. `` Many of these who only recently were regarded inactive and had lost contact with the party branch, who had been regarded as dead wood, are now trying to find their place in life,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said. `` The very certification process should be a school of educating Communists,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> added.
</TEXT>
