 A congresswoman seeking her fifth term could be removed from the ballot because of two minor discrepancies on her declaration of candidacy, authorities said Saturday. Two Democratic candidates said they would decide this week whether to ask the state Board of Elections to invalidate Republican Rep. <PERSON> Claudine </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON>'s candidacy because of a missing middle initial and an address that said `` avenue'' instead of `` street.'' <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>, a convicted murderer running as an independent candidate in the district, said Saturday that he had filed a formal objection with the board based on the two errors. <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON> was the second <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> Republican congressional candidate to encounter a filing error last week. Former state <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> had to withdraw from the race in the state's other district Thursday after a campaign aide failed to file his declaration of candidacy by the 4 p.m. deadline. <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> was automatically disqualified because the law setting the filing deadline allows no exceptions. But <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON> will remain on the ballot unless the Board of Elections upholds an objection against her, election officials said. There was no one in the elections board office Saturday to confirm that <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> had filed his petition. If <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON> is removed from the ballot, she would have to wage a write-in campaign. She is unopposed on the Republican ticket. An aide, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Rendine </PERSON>, said he did not know how the error occurred but he believed <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON> will remain on the ballot. `` The intent of the law is to remove any confusion and make sure that a candid