<HEAD>Episcopalians To Address Issues On Gays, AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>'s 69th General Convention opened Saturday with a church official saying that while marriage among homosexuals and the AIDS epidemic are on the agenda they should n't dominate the meeting. Presiding Bishop <PERSON> Edmond </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> asked about 4,000 people in his opening address to `` look beyond particular issues to what unites us,'' expressing concern that the church could become a `` single-issue church.'' `` I hope that we do not let any one particular issue dominate the convention. That is not to say that issues are not important,'' he said. The triennial convention will look into the issue of setting a policy to recognize `` single-sex marriages.'' `` We have a ministry to the gay community,'' <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> said. `` We are struggling to find out what that means. We are not going to back away from it, because there are some voices that question whether this is the thing to do. `` The way we can be more understanding is to stay in communication and avoid a judgmental approach in this ministry.'' The Rev. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, deputy president of the convention's <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION>, said the church should recognize all relationships regardless of sexual preference `` We have been supportive of -LRB- single-sex -RRB- marriage and we have to get back to that,'' <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said. `` We're being unfaithful to marriage.'' Gay rights became an open issue in the church in 1976 when the general convention affirmed gays as `` children of God,'' decried violence and prejudice against them and asked a special church commission to study whether they should be ordained to the priesthood. In 1979, despite a positive recommendation of the special commission, the convention narrowly defeated a proposal to open the priesthood to gays. Twenty-one bishops, including <PERSON> Browning </PERSON>, immediately declared their opposition to the ban. Despite the ban, gays continued to be ordained since bishops had a wide latitude in interpretation within their dioceses. Also on the convention's agenda are women's roles in the church and compassion toward AIDS victims. Earlier Saturday, in his address to the opening session of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said `` the greatest shame of the Episcopal church is the lack of intensity of faith.'' <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> cited a survey by the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post-L.A. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> news service that showed Episcopalians are less likely than members of other denominations to say religion is `` very important'' in their lives. `` Overall, 55 percent of Americans and 61 percent of Protestants, but only 41 percent of Episcopalians, said that religion was very important,'' <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> has 2.6 million members and 15,000 ordained clergy in 7,500 parishes in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, church officials said.
