ters were trying to cut a hole in the ceiling so they could extinguish the fire burning between the false ceiling and the roof. <PERSON> Aiellos </PERSON> said the dealership, which he estimated was 30 years old, met existing building codes when it was constructed. But revised codes probably would have forced the owners to rethink the design, he said. He did not say how the construction might have been different under current fire codes. The <ORGANIZATION> Bergen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> joined the city's fire department in investigating the cause of the blaze, but preliminary investigation indicated that arson was not to blame, <PERSON> Aiellos </PERSON> said. Company officials declined to comment and <PERSON> Aiellos </PERSON> said authorities could not put a dollar figure on the damage. Killed in the blaze were Capt. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, 54, a 24-year firefighter who had four children; Lt. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Reinhagen </PERSON>, 48, with 23 years in the department and two children; firefighter <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Krejsa </PERSON>, 52, with 24 years' experience and three children; firefighter <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Radumski </PERSON> 38, a 13-year firefighter with one child; and firefighter <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Ennis </PERSON>, 30, a five-year veteran with one child.
