<HEAD>Full Yeltsin Speech Published, Includes Strong Criticism Of
Leaders</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet Party Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Newspapers published on Saturday what television had not shown the day before _ a fired <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> official's stinging criticism of some of the most powerful men in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>, the former <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief who was fired in November, denounced Politburo member <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomentsev </PERSON> and others who served under the late President <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>. <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON> now is blamed for leading the country into a period of stagnation and corruption during his rule from 1964-1982. But <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> also demanded that such hidden subjects as <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> finances be made public along with detailed biographies of the nation's leaders and information about their luxurious summer homes and guest houses. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> made he speech Friday at the final day of the four-day <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> conference. Television showed segments of his address, including his appeal for political rehabilitation but ignored his critical comments. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> was fired as <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> party chief and removed as a non-voting member of the ruling Politburo because of his remarks at a party <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> meeting last October. His comments at that meeting have never been published, but officials said he blamed the bureaucracy for slowing the pace of reform planned by Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorb