<HEAD>New Law Restores Drunken Drivers' Licenses Earlier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new law restored <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> driver's licenses to 530 convicted drunken drivers in time for the Fourth of July weekend. The law, which went into effect Friday, says that first-offense drunken drivers whose licenses had been revoked for at least four months could apply to get their driving privileges back immediately. For those convicted of drunken driving in the future, the license revocation period for a first offense will be three months. The revocation period had been one year. The chance for an early return to the road, before their year was up, drew hundreds of people to the <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> Motor Vehicle Division office even before it opened Friday. `` We processed 214 in less than two hours,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Georgeson </PERSON>, state driver control section chief. `` The line was outside and around the block.'' `` It makes me sick,'' said state Rep. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> McInnis </PERSON>, a former policeman who opposed the amendment making the shorter revocation period retroactive. `` Putting 500 convicted drunken drivers behind the wheel sooner than they should _ it's definitely a step backward.'' The new law aims to toughen drunken-driving enforcement by reducing the legal blood-alcohol threshold defining drunkenness from 0.15 to 0.10 percent. Amendments attached to the bill shortened the license revocation period and provided for the shorter period to apply retroactively. The bill's original sponsor, Sen. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, said he did n't like the idea of reducing the revocation period for first offenders retroactively. However, he said, studies show that very few first offenders go on to become multiple offenders.
