<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Matlovich </PERSON>, a Vietnam War hero whose 1975 discharge from the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> for his avowed homosexuality became a rallying point for gay rights activists, was buried here Saturday with full military honors. <PERSON> Matlovich </PERSON>, 44, died June 22 in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, from complications associated with AIDS, a fatal virus-borne disease whose chief victims have been homosexual men and intravenous drug abusers. He was buried in Congressional Cemetery just 20 blocks from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Capitol in a ceremony that mixed the military pomp of a horse-drawn caisson and a traditional three-volley salute by seven riflemen with eulogies from gay rights activists. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> finally did it right and on <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON>'s terms today,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Kameny </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> gay rights activist who was instrumental in counseling <PERSON> Matlovich </PERSON> on testing the military's ban on homosexuality `` It's a pity that they did n't do it 13 years ago,'' <PERSON> Kameny </PERSON> said as an <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> color guard departed the cemetery. <PERSON> Matlovich </PERSON>, who was awarded a Purple Heart after stepping on a <ORGANIZATION> Viet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cong </ORGANIZATION> land mind and the <ORGANIZATION> Bronze </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> for killing two <ORGANIZATION> Viet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cong </ORGANIZATION> soldiers attacking his post, first challenged the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>'s rules on homosexuality in 1975. At the time, he was a technical sergeant working as a drug and alcohol abuse counselor at <ORGANIZATION> Lang