<HEAD>Rates on International Telephone Calls Increased 700 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rates on international telephone calls have been increased an average 700 percent and on national calls 300 percent, the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Barricada </ORGANIZATION> reported Saturday. <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, vice minister of the <ORGANIZATION> Telecommmunications </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Mail </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, told the newspaper a three-minute call to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> that cost 240 cordobas until Thursday now is 1,920 cordobas. The increase would be from $ 3 to $ 24 at the official rate of 80 cordobas to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar. On the black market a dollar sells for more than 300 cordobas. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> said the monthly telephone rate was increased from 200 to 800 cordobas, or from $ 2.50 to $ 10 at the official rate. The rates, which took effect Friday, follow economic measures announced June 14 that included devaluation of the cordoba from 10 per dollar to 80. Bank interests were increased and salaries boosted 30 percent. Government controls on salaries of industrial workers were lifted and prices freed.
