hile, has arrived in the Soviet city of <LOCATION> Votkinsk </LOCATION>, the site of a plant that formerly built the SS-20 missiles, the most important Soviet weapon to be eliminated under the treaty. The Soviets arriving in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> were greeted by a small group of local residents, including about a dozen <ORGANIZATION> Magna </ORGANIZATION> elementary school children, who held signs reading `` Welcome to Magna.'' Speaking through an interpreter, <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Samarin </PERSON>, the leader of the inspection team, said the time had come to effect the terms of the treaty to eliminate Soviet and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intermediate missiles. `` It is generally accepted that the INF Treaty is an important stage in the relations between our two countries, a first step towards the saving of mankind from the threat of nuclear annhilation,'' he said in a brief, prepared statement. `` We should not be cynical or euphoric aboutthis process,'' said Marine Col. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Connell </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> On-Site </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inspection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's not the millenium, but it is an important step in the peace process. The Soviets mingled briefly with the children, shaking hands and passing out <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> pocket calendars before boarding a bus to their apartments in suburban <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, where they will stay there until quarters are built for them in <LOCATION> Magna </LOCATION>. The all-male contingent traveled to the <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> without wives and families. They will be rotatd periodically with other Soviets, but <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Leeuwen </PERSON>, logistics manager for the <ORGANIZATION> OSIA </ORGANIZATION>, said the schedule will be up to the Soviets. The apartment building where the Soviets are staying has been restricted and is off-limits to the news media, <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Leeuwen </PERSON> said. `` They asked for privacy just to unload,'' he said. `` They ` re tired.'' The `` baseline inspections'' to be conducted within the next two months are designed to verify the exact number of missiles and related components to be destroyed under the treaty. The Soviet inspectors arrived with a 10-member air crew aboard an <ORGANIZATION> Aeroflot </ORGANIZATION> jetliner at <LOCATION> Travis </LOCATION> on Friday, the same day 20 <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> inspectors left for <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and Votkinsk. At the Magna plant, which made Pershing missile rocket motors, the Soviets have the right to monitor the plant's gates for up to 13 years. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> may station inspectors for the same period at a Votkinsk plant that formerly built the SS-20 missiles, the most important Soviet weapon to be eliminted under the treaty. The Soviets were scheduled to announce late Saturday which of the five sites they will visit to conduct the baseline spot checks. The five are a <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> plant in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>; the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s Dugway Proving Ground in western <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>; the <ORGANIZATION> Pueblo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Depot </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pueblo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huachuca </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>; and <ORGANIZATION> Davis-Monthan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>. Altogther, there are 26 missile sites in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and 133 sites in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> that are open to inspection under the treaty The INF pact, the first to allow such on-site inspection, is viewed as a trial for the proposed <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arms </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reduction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION>, which would slash arsenals of long-range superpower nuclear weapons by 30 percent to 50 percent, and involve much more complicated verification procedures.
