<HEAD>FBI Cable Probe Nets Four</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four men accused of illegally selling millions of dollars worth of cable television and satellite descramblers have been following a two-year <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> investigation. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Pirofsky </PERSON>, 43, and <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Pirofsky </PERSON>, 37, both of <LOCATION> Clifton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Zibro </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, 34, of <LOCATION> Cohoes </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Fournier </PERSON>, 36, of Troy, pleaded innocent at their arraignments Thursday and were released on their own recognizance. The illegal sale and manufacture of descramblers is a misdemeanor, punishable by up to one year in prison and a $ 10,000 fine. Officials said the illegal sales ring was among the largest in the country, and sold the components in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION>. `` Indications are that this one is one of the largest, if not the largest,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Signal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theft </ORGANIZATION>, based at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Descramblers decode signals to certain cable television pay channels, allowing viewers to watch the channels without paying for them. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said the typical user saved between $ 30 and $ 40 a month, which otherwise would have been paid to so-called `` premium'' pay channels. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said the industry loses $ 250 million annually to descrambling pirates. Also named in the 86-count indictment were six corporations run by the men under the names P.G. <ORGANIZATION> Video </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Satellite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Starview </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Sone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Video </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Trend </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Video </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, according to <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Scullin </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney for the northern district of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The ring allegedly operated between January 1984 and August 1986, violating federal laws that outlaw the manufacture, distribution and use of cable descramblers by unauthorized individuals, <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and federal prosecutors said. Descramblers can be sold legally to authorized individuals such as cable television companies.
