<HEAD>Peru Rebel Slain in Gas Station Attacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police fatally shot a suspected guerrilla and captured another as insurgents bombed three gasoline stations Saturday, authorities said. Police said the pro-Cuban guerrillas from the <ORGANIZATION> Tupac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Amaru </ORGANIZATION> revolutionary movement staged the attacks to protest a recent 58 percent increase in fuel prices, raising the price of gasoline to 84 cents a gallon. The guerrilla group, which has been active since 1984, frequently launches attacks to protest government policies. Police said the rebels ordered attendants away at gunpoint at all three gas stations and then blew up gas pumps and offices with dynamite. Firefighters and attendants extinguished the fires before flames reached gas storage tanks, police said. Groups of three or four attackers fled in cars from each station, located in widespread areas of the city, police said. When one band was intercepted by a squad car, a gunfight ensued that left one guerrilla dead, they said, adding that another guerrilla was captured and the rest escaped.
