<HEAD>Takeover Stocks Led Market Parade In First Half</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Lasergraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Though a mood of caution and indecision prevailed in the stock market for much of the time, there were still a good many success stories to be told on Wall Street in the first half of 1988. Indeed, in the waning days of June, 31 issues traded on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> had doubled or more from their 1987 closing prices. As any follower of the investment scene might expect, the list of those winners was dominated by stocks of companies that became the targets of takeover or buyout bids. Prominent examples: <ORGANIZATION> Murray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION>, up 175 percent; <PERSON> J.P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, 135 percent; <ORGANIZATION> Arkansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION>, 134 percent; <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, 131 percent; <PERSON> Varo </PERSON>, 130 percent; <ORGANIZATION> Payless </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cashways </ORGANIZATION>, 120 percent; <ORGANIZATION> Federated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>, 119 percent; and <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION>, 112 percent. While the overall averages posted gains for the first half of the year, there were some notable laggards as the market struggled to recover from the beating it took in the crash last fall. It was a test of patience for the 2.7 million-plus owners of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's most widely held stock, which closed June 30 at 26 -RCB-, down 0.9 percent from the end of 1987. <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T holders fared much better than did the many fans of <ORGANIZATION> Genentech </ORGANIZATION>, a high-flying leader in the promising field of biotechnology. <ORGANIZATION> Genentech </ORGANIZATION> shares fell some 35 percent to rank among the first half's biggest <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> percentage change losers, as investors went through a wrenching reappraisal of prospects for a <ORGANIZATION> Genentech </ORGANIZATION> drug used to treat heart-attack patients. Still harder times befell <ORGANIZATION> Coleco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>, the loss-plagued toy and game manufacturer, whose stock fell more than 40 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Coleco </ORGANIZATION> shares, which traded as high as $ 65 a share in 1983 when the company's Cabbage Patch Kids dolls were becoming a national craze, reached mid-1988 in the neighborhood of $ 2. Aside from such individual cases, the market has had trouble establishing any consistent themes so far in 1988. There was no standout strength, for example, either in stocks that would benefit the most from an increase in inflation or in issues that represent a `` disinflation'' play. Analysts said that betokened greater than usual confusion among investors over the direction in which the economy was headed. The year began amid widespread recession fears in the wake of Black Monday last Oct. 19. As it became clear that economic activity was running stronger than almost everybody had forecast, the concern shifted to a possible revival of inflation. By midyear, that scare seemed to have abated somewhat and, sure enough, talk was stirring again of a business slump in 1989. In a compilation by <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of the comparative performance of industry groups in the stock market through June 29, many of the winners drew their strength from takeover bids or battles that affected one or more of their component stocks: For example, textile products, up 65 percent, and department stores, up 49 percent. Notable among the worst performers were some health-care groups _ miscellaneous health care, down 30 percent, and medical products and supplies, down 3 percent _ and high-technology entries like computer software, down 11 percent, and electronic instruments, down 4 percent. For those investors who bet on revived inflation, gold mining stocks failed to pay off, falling nearly 5 percent.
</TEXT>
