<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions July 2-3</NOTE>
<HEAD>Volatility Marks First Half Of '88; Economists More Bullish For
Remainder</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If the first half of 1988 is any indication of what the rest of the year will be like for bonds and interest rates, better hang on to your hats now. `` Anybody who survived the first half of'88 had to have had their seatbelt on,'' said <PERSON> Irwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Kellner </PERSON>, chief economist for <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` The market was extremely volatile.'' Bonds started out the year on a strong note, with interest rates continuing to decline following last fall's stock market crash. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> had relaxed its credit policies on the widespread belief the crash might affect spending habits and push the economy into a recession. And declining oil prices also played an important role in dampening any inflation concerns. But as the economy showed surprising resilience, interest rates started to climb again and bonds lost their luster. Concern turned to the possibility of higher inflation and the interest-rate outlook overseas along with the dollar's instability in foreign exchange. Those factors continue to plague the credit markets, although rates have eased lately on the recent strength of the dollar. A firm <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency makes dollar-denominated bonds and notes more attractive to foreigners and lessens the prospects of higher inflation, which erodes the value of fixed-income securities. `` If you're a bond trader and you made money in the first six months of the year, then you were a superstar,'' said <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldinger </PERSON>, who runs the <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, investment banking firm <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` Most of us ended up about even.'' `` The interesting thing is that with all the ups and down we've had, we have n't changed all that much,'' noted <PERSON> Maury </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, chief economist for <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION> Bond prices and yields right now are about where they were at the start of the year. For instance, the yield on the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s 30-year bond, the most widely-watched issue in the credit markets, stood at 8.93 percent on Jan. 4. On the last day of June it was 8.85 percent, down from 8.92 percent in the previous session. And the <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Bond Index, which measures price movements on all outstanding <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> issues with maturities of a year or longer, looked at the end of June like it had barely budged from early January. In the intervening months, however, prices and yields proceeded on a veritable roller-coaster ride. The 30-year bond, which peaked at 10.4 percent the day of the market crash last October, tumbled to a low of 8.29 percent on Feb. 5 and jumped to a high of 9.35 percent on May 23. Commercial lending rates followed suit. Major banks lowered their prime lending rates _ used to set rates on most corporate and consumer loans _ a quarter of a percentage point to 8.5 percent on Feb. 2, then raised them to 9 percent on May 11. Mortgage rates followed a similar pattern. For a conventional 30-year fixed-rate mortgage, rates ranged from a low of 9.84 percent in mid-February to a high of 10.58 percent in late May and early June, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The confusion in the marketplace scared away some municipal and corporate issuers. For the first six months, the volume of municipal issues totaled $ 52.76 billion, compared with $ 58.13 billion a year ago. The volume of corporate issues fell to $ 141.4 billion from $ 157 billion in 1987. `` Right now, sentiment is cautiously bullish,'' based largely on the dollar's recent strength, said <PERSON> Kellner </PERSON> of Manufacturers Hanover. But he said bond investors are keeping an eye on the Midwestern drought and what effects that might have on food prices and inflation _ although most economists say the drought's impact probably wo n't be felt until the beginning of next year. Some economists predict a drop in interest rates for the remainder of 1988, based in part on the declining oil market, the firmer dollar and the feeling that the economy eventually will run out of steam. But as <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> concedes, what happened in the first half of 1988 `` goes to show how difficult it is to predict.''
</TEXT>
