<HEAD>Rising Demand, Drought Fears Keep Pushing Sugar Prices Higher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Rising demand from the Far East has helped push sugar futures prices to 6 -LCB- - year highs, and analysts say the Midwestern drought has sparked an increase in bullish speculation that could drive prices higher still On the other hand, any hint that the rally is running of steam could send the market plunging as nervous traders on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Coffee, <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> scurry to take profits _ or cut their losses, experts say Sugar prices have risen steadily since bottoming out at about 2.75 cents a pound in mid-1985 when world stockpiles stood at record highs. Growing demand and declining production have gradually reduced the surplus until it now stands just above the critically low level of 30 percent of the anticipated 1988-89 demand, according to <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Weissman </PERSON> <PERSON> Ganes </PERSON>, an analyst with the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. In contrast to the slow, steady gains during much of the past 3 years, sugar prices for near-month delivery have skyrocketed in the last two months, from about 8 cents a pound at the end of April to more than 13 cents a pound at the end of June. Moves by <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> during the past year to increase the availability of sugar in that country has had a profound impact on the market, said <PERSON> Erik </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunlaevy </PERSON>, a trader with New York-based commodities and brokerage firm <ORGANIZATION> Balfour </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maclaine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` Basically, the government of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> decided to let the Chinese fulfill their desires for sugar,'' he said. `` They decentralized the purchasing to a certain extent, so you have different entities buying sugar instead of one central purchasing agency.'' He said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> ordinarily buys its sugar from <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and other exporters in the Eastern Hemisphere. But the increased demand from the Chinese has forced those producers to raise their prices, prompting <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and other Far Eastern consumer nations to shop for lower-priced sugar in the West. Caribbean nations supply much of the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hemisphere </LOCATION>'s sugar, and <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> sugar is traditionally the type that gets delivered on the Coffee, <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Dunlaevy </PERSON> said. Thus, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s increased demand is largely responsible for the sharp rise in sugar futures prices Exacerbating the situation is the drought, which threatens to substantially reduce yields of sugar beets in the <LOCATION> Red </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> region of <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, analysts said. `` That's the largest beet crop in this country, so the beet crop here could be down 500,000 to 700,000 tons,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Oxnard </PERSON>, vice president of commodities trading for <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Clifton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> `` On a worldwide basis, that's not a huge number but it's a further drawdown in stocks,'' he said. The drought has also increased bullish speculation in sugar futures, just as it has in virtually every other market for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agricultural products. `` I know there are traders who have one eye on soybeans and one eye on sugar and when beans go up, they buy sugar,'' <ORGANIZATION> Oxnard </ORGANIZATION> said. `` To some degree all these markets have just piggybacked on top of each other.'' One measure of market speculation is `` open interest,'' the number of buy or sell orders that have not been canceled out by an offsetting order. Since late April, open interest in sugar futures has expanded from less than 130,000 to nearly 170,000. `` A large part of the open interest is speculative in nature, representing a lot of fund and commission-house speculators,'' Ms. <PERSON> Ganes </PERSON> said. Although many analysts, including Ms. <PERSON> Ganes </PERSON>, expect sugar prices to climb higher in the near term, they acknowledged that prices could also fall very rapidly. `` If the market does show signs of weakening, -LRB- speculators -RRB- will be fairly quick at taking a profit and that could result in a sharp turn in the market,'' Ms. <PERSON> Ganes </PERSON> said. `` The people who got in at the higher levels are going to be quicker to get out, and that could exaggerate the correction.''
</TEXT>
